Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for the C++ iterator that BlockSci exposes.  
It consists of  

* an OCaml interface file **`blocksci.mli`** that describes the public API,  
* a single C++ source file **`blocksci_stubs.cpp`** that implements the OCaml‑C++ bridge.  

The design follows the usual “opaque‑custom‑value” pattern:

| OCaml type | What it really is in C++ | Lifetime handling |
|------------|--------------------------|-------------------|
| `collection` | `BlockChain*` – a pointer to the BlockSci index object | allocated in `open_collection`, freed in `close_collection` (or automatically when the OCaml value is GC‑collected). |
| `block`      | `Block*` – a pointer to a single Block object returned by the iterator | allocated just before the user callback is invoked and freed immediately afterwards.  This keeps the GC‑graph tiny and avoids keeping the whole chain alive. |

The iterator itself is **not exposed** – the only way to walk the chain is through `iter_blocks`, which calls an OCaml function for each block.  The callback may raise an exception to abort the walk; the exception is propagated back to the caller.

---

## 1.  OCaml interface – `blocksci.mli`

```ocaml
(* blocksci.mli – public OCaml API for the BlockSci C++ library *)

(** Opaque handle to a BlockSci collection (the on‑disk index). *)
type collection

(** Opaque handle to a single Block.  The only way to obtain a [block] is
    via [iter_blocks]; the value is valid only for the duration of the
    callback. *)
type block

(** Open a BlockSci collection that lives in the directory [path].
    Raises [Failure] if the directory cannot be opened or the index
    cannot be read. *)
val open_collection : string -> collection

(** Close a collection explicitly.  The underlying C++ object is freed.
    It is also freed automatically when the OCaml value is garbage‑collected,
    so calling this function is optional but can be useful to release
    resources early. *)
val close_collection : collection -> unit

(** Basic accessors for a [block].  All of them return freshly allocated OCaml
    values; the caller must not keep the [block] value after the callback
    returns. *)
val block_hash      : block -> string      (** SHA‑256 hash of the block header. *)
val block_height    : block -> int         (** Height (0‑based) of the block. *)
val block_timestamp : block -> float       (** Unix epoch timestamp (seconds). *)

(** Iterate over *all* blocks of a collection.  For each block the user‑supplied
    function [f] is called with a fresh [block] value.  If [f] raises an
    exception the iteration stops and the exception is re‑raised to the
    caller.  The order of iteration is the natural top‑to‑bottom order
    (genesis → tip). *)
val iter_blocks : collection -> (block -> unit) -> unit
```

